06378nam a22009255i 9780813545059DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20082008nju    fo  d z      eng d  a97808135450597 a10.36019/97808135450592doi  a(DE-B1597)530294  a(OCoLC)1156983568  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anjucUS-NJ 7aART0000002bisacsh04a700.1/03097322200aUnderstanding the Arts and Creative Sector in the United States /ced. by Ruth Ann Stewart, Joni Maya Cherbo, Margaret Jane Wyszomirski. 1aNew Brunswick, NJ : bRutgers University Press, c[2008] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (224 p.) :b2  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aRutgers Series: The Public Life of the Arts00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart One. Defining the Arts and Creative Sector -- t1. Toward an Arts and Creative Sector -- t2. Interrelations in the Arts and Creative Sector -- t3. Field Building: The Road to Cultural Policy Studies in the United States -- tPart Two. Field Issues -- t4. The Universality of the Arts in Human Life -- t5. About Artists -- t6. Art and Cultural Participation at the Heart of Community Life -- t7. The Arts and Artist in Urban Revitalization -- t8. The Evolution of Arts and Cultural Districts -- t9. Capital, Commerce, and the Creative Industries -- t10. Internet as Medium: Art, Law, and the Digital Environment -- t11. Historic Preservation in the United States -- t12. Between Cooperation and Conflict: International Trade in Cultural Goods and Services -- t13. Identity and Cultural Policy -- tNotes on Contributors0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe arts and creative sector is one of the nation's broadest, most important, and least understood social and economic assets, encompassing both nonprofit arts and cultural organizations, for-profit creative companies, such as advertising agencies, film producers, and commercial publishers, and community-based artistic activities. The thirteen essays in this timely book demonstrate why interest in the arts and creative sector has accelerated in recent years, and the myriad ways that the arts are crucial to the social and national agenda and the critical issues and policies that relate to their practice. Leading experts in the field show, for example, how arts and cultural policies are used to enhance urban revitalization, to encourage civic engagement, to foster new forms of historic preservation, to define national identity, to advance economic development, and to regulate international trade in cultural goods and services. Illuminating key issues and reflecting the rapid growth of the field of arts and cultural policy, this book will be of interest to students at both the undergraduate and graduate levels, to arts educators and management professionals, government agency and foundation officials, and researchers and academics in the cultural policy field.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aArt patronagezUnited States. 0aArts and societyzUnited States. 0aArtszUnited StatesxManagement. 0aCultural industrieszUnited States. 0aGovernment aid to the artszUnited States. 7aART / General.2bisacsh1 aBurgess, Chris N., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherbo, Joni Maya, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCherbo, Joni Maya, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDissanayake, Ellen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGalligan, Ann M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJackson, Maria Rosario, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Antoinette J., econtributor.4ctb4